----
[B]
Date: Tue 30 Mar 2021
Source: CNBC [abridged, edited]
https://www.cnbc.com/2021/03/30/covid-in-brazil-completely-out-of-control-says-sao-paulo-based-reporter.html


Brazil just reached a grim COVID-19 milestone, and a reporter based in Sao Paulo doesn't see the situation improving in the near future.

"We have people dying because of lack of oxygen, people are literally suffocating," Patricia Campos Mello, a reporter for Folha de Sao Paulo, told CNBC's "The News with Shepard Smith" on Tuesday [30 Mar 2021]. "There are no medications for intubation, there are no ICU beds. It's a combination of lack of planning and just denialism of the seriousness of the disease."

"The situation is completely out of control," Campos Mello added.

Campos Mello comments came after Brazil registered on Tuesday a daily record tally of COVID deaths, recording more than 3,700 deaths, according to data from Brazil's health ministry. Brazil has the second-most COVID deaths in the world with [over 322 000], trailing only the United States, according to Johns Hopkins University. On top of that, less than 2% of Brazil's population has received at least one vaccine dose.

Campos Mello noted the world can learn from the mistakes in Brazil.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The toll of COVID in Brazil has been truly staggering, trailing only the US in overall numbers of cases and deaths. It is clear from multiple reports that the healthcare system has become overwhelmed in many parts of the country, with rationing and waiting lists for ICU beds. Not coincidentally, Brazil has largely not adopted non-pharmaceutical interventions for outbreak control or mitigation. While vaccination has begun, it appears unlikely to achieve adequate levels to reduce transmission in the near or even medium term. - Mod.LM]

